data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed:**

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|----------|-------------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Reports actual vs expected count on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Asserts exactly one match and returns it |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` since there's no built-in "all satisfy predicate" assertion. Alternatively, you could loop and assert each one if you want per-item failure messages.
